<Layout title="llm-osec — Ian Bragg">
  <h1>llm-osec</h1>
  <p class="tagline">OWASP LLM Top 10 scanner — a CLI that probes a deployed LLM application for the top categories of risk and produces a structured findings report.</p>

  <div class="signals">
    <span class="signal">Status: in development</span>
    <span class="signal">Python · Claude SDK · CISSP-flavored</span>
  </div>

  <h2>Why this exists</h2>
  <p>
    Most security tooling for traditional applications (SAST, DAST, fuzzers)
    does not catch the failure modes specific to LLM-powered applications:
    prompt injection, sensitive data leakage through hallucination, insecure
    output handling, training-data poisoning, and the other risks documented
    in the <a href="https://owasp.org/www-project-top-10-for-large-language-model-applications/">OWASP Top 10 for LLM Applications</a>.
    Security teams adopting LLM features are mostly hand-rolling tests or
    pulling pieces from research repos.
  </p>
  <p>
    <code>llm-osec</code> is a focused, opinionated scanner that runs a
    library of probes against a target LLM endpoint and writes a structured
    report (severity, category, evidence, suggested mitigation). The goal is
    something a CISSP / AppSec engineer can drop into a CI pipeline or run
    on demand, not a research toolkit that requires a PhD to operate.
  </p>

  <h2>What it covers (MVP scope)</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>LLM01 — Prompt Injection.</strong> Direct + indirect injection probes; system-prompt exfiltration attempts.</li>
    <li><strong>LLM02 — Insecure Output Handling.</strong> XSS / SSRF / injection vectors smuggled through model output.</li>
    <li><strong>LLM06 — Sensitive Information Disclosure.</strong> Memory / cache probing; system-prompt leakage.</li>
    <li><strong>LLM08 — Excessive Agency.</strong> Tool-use boundary probes when the target exposes function calling.</li>
    <li><strong>LLM10 — Model Theft.</strong> Output-distillation rate-limiting checks.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Approach</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Probe library encoded as Markdown with metadata + expected-failure signatures — easy to extend, easy to audit.</li>
    <li>Claude as oracle for evaluating ambiguous probe responses (signature match alone is too brittle for prompt-injection success).</li>
    <li>Pluggable target backends: any HTTP endpoint that takes JSON in / JSON out, with adapters for Anthropic / OpenAI / Ollama / generic REST.</li>
    <li>Report output: JSON (machine), Markdown (human), and a printable HTML one-pager.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Where it goes</h2>
  <p>
    Open-source on GitHub. Becomes the foundation of a productized AI-security
    consulting offering once the W-2 transition is complete and contract
    constraints clear.
  </p>

  <p class="muted">
    <em>Repository link will appear here once the initial commits are public.</em>
  </p>
</Layout>
